    id: 'how-to-stop-3-putting',
    slug: '/how-to-stop-3-putting/',
    thumbnail: '/images/thumbnails/how-to-stop-3-putting-thumb.webp',
    category: 'improve-game',
    pageType: 'tutorial',
    tag: 'TUTORIAL',
    emoji: '🎯',
    thumb: 'purple',
    words: '1,900',
    datePublished: '2025-07-09',
    dateModified:  '2026-04-14',
    updateLog: [
      { date: 'Apr 14, 2026', note: 'Annual freshness review — verified pricing and availability.' },
    ],
    title:        'How to Stop 3-Putting — 5 Drills That Fix It Fast',
    titleDisplay: '🎯 How to Stop 3-Putting — 5 Drills That Fix It Fast (2026)',
    bottomLine: 'Three-putting is a distance control problem, not an aiming problem. The fastest fix: practice lag putts from 30 feet — if you can consistently stop the ball within 3 feet, three-putts disappear.',
    description:  'You lipped out from 4 feet on 18. Again. Five drills that fix your distance control and short putts — no practice green required, just 20 minutes.',
    excerpt:      'Three-putting costs the average weekend golfer 4-6 strokes per round. These 5 drills fix the three root causes in 2-3 sessions on the putting green.',
    intro: '3-putting costs the average weekend golfer 4-6 strokes per round — more than almost any other single problem. The causes are always one of three things: poor distance control on long putts, poor alignment on short putts, or a yippy stroke under 4 feet. Here is the fix for all three.',
    toc: [
      'Why you 3-putt (the real reasons)',
      'Drill 1: The Gate Drill for short putts',
      'Drill 2: The Ladder Drill for distance control',
      'Drill 3: The Clock Drill for 6-footers',
      'Drill 4: The Towel Drill for lag putting',
      'Drill 5: Pre-round putting warm-up routine',
      'Equipment that helps',
    ],
    sections: [
      {
        h2: 'Why You 3-Putt (The Real Reasons)',
        body: 'Most golfers blame their putting stroke. The actual causes are: 1) Leaving a 40-foot putt 15 feet short or long (distance control), 2) Misaligning the face on 4-foot comeback putts (alignment), and 3) Decelerating through impact on short putts (confidence). The stroke is rarely the problem on putts under 8 feet — it is everything else.',
      },
      {
        h2: 'Drill 1: The Gate Drill (Fixes Short Putts)',
        body: 'Place two tees in the ground just wider than your putter head, 1 foot in front of your ball on a straight 4-foot putt. Make 20 putts. If you hit a tee, your face was open or closed at impact. This drill gives you immediate feedback without needing a coach. Do 20 putts before every round. Within 2 weeks, short putts become automatic.',
      },
      {
        h2: 'Drill 2: The Ladder Drill (Fixes Distance Control)',
        body: 'Place 5 balls at 10, 20, 30, 40, and 50 feet from the hole. Putt each one trying to stop it within 18 inches of the hole. Do not try to make them — just hit the right speed. This is the most effective distance control drill ever designed. Three sessions per week for 2 weeks eliminates most distance control 3-putts.',
      },
      {
        h2: 'Drill 3: The Clock Drill (Fixes 6-Footers)',
        body: 'Place 8 balls around the hole at 6 feet — like the numbers on a clock face. Make all 8 in a row. If you miss, start over. This drill builds both alignment and confidence under pressure. It is uncomfortable by design. Tour pros use it daily. If you can make all 8 consistently, you will not 3-putt from 6 feet again.',
      },
      {
        h2: 'Drill 4: The Towel Drill (Fixes Lag Putting)',
        body: 'Place a golf towel 3 feet past the hole. From 40 feet, putt to stop the ball between the hole and the towel — on the hole or just past it. Never short, never more than 3 feet past. This trains the instinct to leave the ball on the high side and within tap-in range. Do 10 putts per session.',
      },
      {
        h2: 'Equipment That Helps',
        body: 'A putting mirror ($22) shows you face alignment and eye position simultaneously — the fastest way to find and fix a systematic alignment error. The Eyeline putting cup ($29) trains short putt entry angle. Neither replaces the drills above, but both accelerate improvement if used alongside them.',
      },
    ],
    faq: [
      { q: 'What causes 3-putting most often?', a: 'Poor distance control on long putts is the primary cause of 3-putting for most weekend golfers. A 40-foot putt left 15 feet from the hole guarantees a 3-putt. The second most common cause is misalignment on the resulting short comeback putt. The solution: spend 80% of your practice time on putts from 20-50 feet, not 3-footers.' },
      { q: 'How do you eliminate 3-putts from inside 10 feet?', a: 'Three-putts from inside 10 feet are almost always an alignment or confidence problem, not a distance control problem. Use the Gate Drill (two tees one club-length in front of the ball, just wider than the putter head) for 20 putts before every round. Within 2 weeks the alignment issues that cause short misses disappear.' },
      { q: 'What is a good 3-putt rate for an amateur golfer?', a: 'Tour pros average around 1-2% 3-putt rate. Single-digit handicap amateurs average around 5-8%. Bogey golfers average 15-20% — meaning 3 to 4 holes per round. Getting that below 10% (under 2 three-putts per round) is realistic for any golfer who practices the Ladder Drill regularly.' },
    ],
    sources: [{ label: 'TrackMan — Lag Putting Distance Control Data', url: 'https://blog.trackmangolf.com/putting-stats/' }, { label: 'PGA Tour — Strokes Gained: Putting Statistics', url: 'https://www.pgatour.com/stats/detail/02564' }],
